{
  "texts": [
    "open-source LLMs can be scrutinized, tailored, and enhanced by a wider user base, fostering a diverse group of contributors and improving the overall quality and fairness of the models.",
    "Furthermore, open-source LLMs offer significant data protection benefits.",
    "They are designed not to share data with third parties, enhancing security and confidentiality.",
    "For these reasons, the academic community is increasingly advocating for the use of open-source LLMs [27,36].",
    "This transition would not only broaden researchers' access to these tools but also promote a more open and reproducible research culture.To address these questions, we extend previous research [13] to compare the performance of two widely-used open-source LLMs, LLaMA and FLAN, with that of GPT 3.5 as well as MTurkers, using eleven text annotation tasks distributed across four datasets."
  ]
}